<p>Using digital microscopy, Schoenemann and colleagues report that a number of internal eye structures are very similar to those of the compound eyes of modern insects and crustaceans. </p>



<p>One such structure is the ommatidia, a visual unit that is made up of light-detecting cells grouped around a transparent tube called a rhabdom (rodlike structures found in the eyes of insects). A thick lens and what looks like a crystalline cone topped each visual unit, directing light through them before being focused onto the rhabdom.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="768" src="https://cdn.zmescience.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/trilobite-2_image_jpeg-1024x768.jpeg" alt="" class="wp-image-179554" srcset="https://cdn.zmescience.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/trilobite-2_image_jpeg-1024x768.jpeg 1024w, https://cdn.zmescience.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/trilobite-2_image_jpeg-1536x1152.jpeg 1536w, https://cdn.zmescience.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/trilobite-2_image_jpeg-750x563.jpeg 750w, https://cdn.zmescience.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/trilobite-2_image_jpeg-1140x855.jpeg 1140w, https://cdn.zmescience.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/08/trilobite-2_image_jpeg.jpeg 1600w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /><figcaption><em>Aulacopleura kionickii</em>’s left eye. Credit: Brigitte Schoenemann</figcaption></figure>



<p>So how did it see? Very differently from humans, that&#8217;s for sure. Eyes made up of dozens of facets would have generated a mosaic of images, where each image captures a snapshot of the trilobite&#8217;s environment. This would have made the creature well adapted to distinguishing obstacles, shelters, shapes, and other organisms &#8212; particularly predatory cephalopods known to feast on trilobites.</p><div class="jeg_ad jeg_ad_article jnews_content_inline_3_ads  "><div class='ads-wrapper align-center '><div class='ads_shortcode'><!-- Tag ID: zmescience_300x250_InContent_3 -->
